english:
  title: In Praise of Tsushima Island
  author: Kim Hyn
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Beyond the sea lies a world unto itself,
    where islands gather into settlements.
    The people are mostly fishermen,
    and half the villages are salt-workers' homes.

    Even children wear swords at their sides,
    and women know well how to work the oars.
    They thatch their roofs with reeds
    and split bamboo to make arrows.

    Bamboo fences teem with crabs,
    while rocky shores yield little grain.
    They boil wild roots in their broths,
    and feather their quivers with chicken plumes.

    Shells and clams sustain their stores,
    pepper and tea command their trade.
    They heal their ills with mugwort and fire,
    and read the bones to divine the weather.

    They make offerings to the Buddha,
    and fugitives gather at their shrines.
    They remove their shoes to honor their elders,
    and sit without shunning their fathers.

    Their hair is coiled and teeth often stained,
    their palms pressed together with bended backs.
    Their eyes flash quick with savage pride,
    they kill without hesitation when provoked.

    Their speech runs loose and ceaseless,
    yet they leap with joy at wrestling games.
    Their toasts mock all ceremony,
    and their feasts astonish with strange creations.

    They pile mountain fruits—tangerines and citrons,
    and sea treasures—great serpents and beasts.
    Their banter chirps like birds,
    their songs croak like frogs.

    They dance with flashing blades,
    masks emerging from painted curtains.
    The host shows lavish warmth,
    while guests laugh and revel.

    To wander so far tastes sweet as cane,
    where flavors blend both bitter and kind.
    Yet I must depart and return home early—
    beautiful as it is, this land is not mine.
  footnotes:
    - Tsushima Island (對馬島) lies between Korea and Japan, historically significant in East Asian trade and diplomacy.
    - The poem catalogs the distinctive customs, crafts, and social practices of the island inhabitants, presenting them with anthropological curiosity and poetic affection.
    - The closing lines express the bittersweet tension between appreciation for foreign lands and the irreducible pull of home—a common theme in classical Korean travel poetry.
